  "body": "### Description\r\n\r\nDISCLAIMER: I am not sure if this I technical possible with all the native stuff and so on. \r\n\r\nI have an application that access the file system to read/write files. Testing with `@QuarkusTest` is a piece of cake as all the data is on my local fs. When It comes to containerized native integration testing this gets a bit messy. The solution I currently use is an extra API which can create  or read testdata inside of the container. \r\nThis means I have code for testing in `main` which already is definitly not good practice. I need to secure the API in production mode, so it is not callable anymore. This is error prone and poses a risk.\r\n\r\nSo it would be nice if I could write the files directly into the container. Or into a volume mount.\r\n\r\n### Implementation ideas\r\n\r\nIn my imagination this would be configurable somehow like this:\r\n`quarkus.test.container.volume-mounts.\"C:\\dev\\projects\\myproject\"=\\home\\myContainerFolder`\r\nwhich would lead to the docker container under test is started with `-v C:\\dev\\projects\\myproject:\\home\\myContainerFolder`\r\nNow I still can create all my testdata on my local fs and everything works as expected without any extra messy hacking.\r\n\r\n",
